   =20
      Shareholder voting
   =20
 =20

We have talked a few times recently about a stylized fact of US public comp=
anies, which is that retail shareholders don=E2=80=99t vote. When a company=
 has its annual meeting and sends out proxy statements and asks its shareho=
lders to vote on questions like =E2=80=9Cshould our board of directors be r=
e-elected=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdo you approve of management=E2=80=99s comp=
ensation plan=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdo you approve of=C2=A0our audit firm=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cshould we write a report about our greenhouse gas em=
issions,=E2=80=9D its ordinary individual shareholders throw those proxy st=
atements in the garbage and do not vote on those questions.
One reason that retail shareholders don=E2=80=99t vote is that it is hard t=
o reach them: They have busy lives, they get a lot of junk mail, they throw=
 it all away. Plus the company itself generally   won=E2=80=99t know who it=
s retail shareholders are, and will have to communicate using a multi-tiere=
d indirect approach (sending proxies to brokers who send them to shareholde=
rs, etc.) that doesn=E2=80=99t reach shareholders very efficiently.
Another reason that retail shareholders don=E2=80=99t vote is that it would=
 be an insane use of their time. If you own shares in 50 companies, and you=
 want to vote those shares in an informed way, you have to read 50 proxy st=
atements each year. Each proxy might be 50 to 100 pages long, so you are ta=
lking about thousands of pages of reading. Here is Exxon Mobil Corp.=E2=80=
=99s  proxy statement for its 2022 annual meeting, which runs to 86 pages. =
Shareholders have to vote to re-elect 11 members of the board of directors.=
 They have to vote to ratify Exxon=E2=80=99s independent auditors and to ap=
prove its executive compensation. And then there are seven proposals that s=
hareholders have made =E2=80=94 some of the summaries on the proxy card are=
=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cremove executive perquisites,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Creport on sc=
enario analysis,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Creport on plastic production=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0that also require votes. So just for Exxon you need to come =
to a view=C2=A0on 20 different proposals. You have 49 more proxies to read.
None of these votes are binding. If a majority of=C2=A0shareholders vote ag=
ainst a public company=E2=80=99s director=C2=A0in an ordinary uncontested v=
ote, that director=C2=A0will probably have to submit a resignation, but the=
 board generally has the option to reject the resignation: The shareholder =
vote itself is not enough to remove that director. The   auditor ratificati=
on=C2=A0and  executive compensation votes are nonbinding; it is embarrassin=
g for the company to lose them but has no obvious immediate effect. The sha=
reholder proposals are especially nonbinding: They generally call for the c=
ompany to write reports about things that the shareholders don=E2=80=99t li=
ke=C2=A0(plastic production, etc.). Even if a majority of shareholders vote=
 for these proposals,=C2=A0the company is not required to write the reports=
. Even if it does write the reports, it doesn=E2=80=99t have to do anything=
 about them. There is not really a mechanism for the shareholders to say =
=E2=80=9Cstop producing plastics=E2=80=9D and make the company actually do =
it.
So if you are a shareholder and you hold 100 shares of stock of Exxon, you =
might reasonably think: =E2=80=9CNone of this makes any difference to me at=
 all. I just want my stock to go up, and none of this stuff will make my st=
ock go up or down no matter how I vote. I have better things to do.=E2=80=
=9D So you throw out the proxy.
Now, to be fair, sometimes there are important binding votes. If a public c=
ompany agrees to be acquired in a merger, its shareholders will have to vot=
e to approve the merger; if it doesn=E2=80=99t get enough votes then the me=
rger won=E2=80=99t happen. If the company is trading at $10 and the merger =
price is $15, and you don=E2=80=99t vote and the merger fails, you will mis=
s out on $5 per share. Sometimes companies need shareholder approval to, sa=
y,   issue more stock, or   extend their deadline to do a deal, and getting=
 or not getting that approval will make a real economic difference. Sometim=
es an activist will launch a proxy fight, which will lead to a=C2=A0binding=
=C2=A0shareholder vote on two different slates of possible board members wi=
th different strategies.=C2=A0In fact this  happened at Exxon in 2021: An a=
ctivist ran a proxy fight to put new directors on the board to try to move =
the company toward renewables faster; the activist won.
If you get a proxy statement like that, you might want to vote your shares,=
 because your vote could have an impact on the value of your stock. But you=
r vote won=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0that=C2=A0much of an impact, because you hol=
d 100 shares and there are billions of shares. In Exxon=E2=80=99s proxy fig=
ht last year, there were 16 candidates, and the=C2=A012 candidates who got =
the most votes were elected to the board. The person in 12th place (the low=
est-ranked winner)=C2=A0got 1,174,445,208 votes; the person in 13th place (=
the top loser) got 1,173,545,328. That=E2=80=99s a difference of 899,880 sh=
ares out of almost 1.2 billion, or about 0.08%, an incredibly close and har=
d-fought proxy fight. Also though that margin is=C2=A0like 9,000 times your=
 little block of 100 shares. Your vote wouldn=E2=80=99t have mattered. And =
that=E2=80=99s about as close as proxy fights realistically get. Even in th=
is hard-fought binding contest about the strategic direction of Exxon, it=
=C2=A0was still a waste of time for you=C2=A0to vote.
Also, even if you thought =E2=80=9Cwell I=E2=80=99ll vote on things like me=
rgers and proxy fights where it might matter, but not on uncontested direct=
or elections where it doesn=E2=80=99t,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0you=E2=80=99d have a p=
roblem, which is that you=E2=80=99d have to=C2=A0pay attention and find out=
. What, you=E2=80=99re going to read every 80-page proxy statement to see i=
f there=E2=80=99s anything good in it? A much easier heuristic is: =E2=80=
=9CMost votes don=E2=80=99t matter, and even on the ones that do matter my =
vote is unlikely to be decisive, so I am going to throw out all the proxy s=
tatements without reading them.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
This is just obvious normal stuff. If you are an individual shareholder, wh=
at you do is (1) buy stock in companies that you like, (2) not buy stock in=
 companies that you don=E2=80=99t like, and (3) if you start to dislike a c=
ompany whose stock you own, you sell it. A fourth approach of buying stock =
in companies and trying to=C2=A0change them=C2=A0via shareholder voting wou=
ld be=C2=A0extremely odd, which is why very few retail investors do it.
  [1]

If you are the gigantic institutional asset manager BlackRock Inc., your ca=
lculation is very different, in a number of ways:
=09You own millions of shares of every public company, so your vote, on con=
tested binding issues, matters. You might very well be the deciding vote on=
 a merger or a proxy fight, which might make a material difference to the v=
alue of your shares.=09Even on the nonbinding stuff, you will care, because=
 you own every public company and you are playing a long game. You might de=
cide something like =E2=80=9Cour companies should be reducing greenhouse ga=
s emissions,=E2=80=9D and then you might think about how to make them do th=
at. There are approaches that are nonbinding=C2=A0but persuasive.=C2=A0(You=
 might have quiet one-on-one chats with the company=E2=80=99s managers abou=
t emissions.) But as a huge shareholder there are also approaches that are =
binding. (You might support a proxy fight, as BlackRock apparently did at E=
xxon, to throw out directors who don=E2=80=99t do what you want.) And then =
everything else sort of exists in the shadow of those binding approaches. I=
f you are BlackRock and you think a company pollutes too much, you might vo=
te your shares in support of a nonbinding shareholder resolution saying =E2=
=80=9Cthe company should write a report about pollution.=E2=80=9D If that r=
esolution gets majority support =E2=80=94=C2=A0or even a large minority =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0that=C2=A0will be embarrassing for the directors. If they conti=
nue to pollute too much, you might vote no on executive pay or director re-=
election: again nonbinding, but even more embarrassing, and also a=C2=A0sig=
nal that next year you might support an activist proxy fight and actually t=
hrow out the directors.=C2=A0All of this stuff is subtle and coded, but the=
 point is that the shareholder vote is one tool that BlackRock has to expre=
ss its desires, and BlackRock=E2=80=99s desires matter a lot to public-comp=
any executives because BlackRock owns like 8% of their stock.=09Voting on t=
he nonbinding stuff might have some marketing value. =E2=80=9CWe care about=
 the environment and pressure companies to do better, as you can see from o=
ur voting record,=E2=80=9D you might want to be able to say, in marketing y=
our funds to potential investors.
  [2]
 Environmental, social and governance investing is hot (though controversia=
l) now, and voting on shareholder proposals is a way to signal your ESG com=
mitments.=09Because you own trillions of dollars of stock, your bar for eco=
nomic relevance is in some sense lower. If you think that writing a report =
on greenhouse gas emissions might add 0.01% to the value of Exxon=E2=80=99s=
 stock, well, BlackRock owns like $24 billion of Exxon stock, so adding 0.0=
1% would be worth $2.4 million to BlackRock=E2=80=99s investors. Worth an a=
fternoon of someone=E2=80=99s time reading a proxy. But if you=E2=80=99re a=
n individual with 100 shares, that 0.01% is worth about $0.92 to you.=09Unl=
ike retail shareholders, you=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0just sell shares in th=
e companies you don=E2=80=99t like: A lot of your money is in index funds, =
which are mandated to hold all the companies. So it is rational to try to p=
ressure them with voting rather than just dumping their stocks when they do=
 things you don=E2=80=99t like.=09Your whole job is paying attention to the=
 important issues at the companies you invest in, unlike a retail investor =
who has a day job and has to read proxy statements in the evening after a l=
ong day at work. You are a fiduciary for your clients, so you have to do a =
good and careful job of paying attention.=09You have thousands of employees=
, so you can have a couple of them specialize in reading proxies. They=E2=
=80=99ll get good at it, they=E2=80=99ll know what to look for, so they can=
 use their time efficiently rather than reading every 80-page proxy cover t=
o cover with a pen in their hands. And because you care mostly about system=
ic issues, they can develop pretty good rules of thumb about what sorts of =
proposals they should and should not vote for.
  [3]

=09Just technologically, the voting=C2=A0systems for institutional investor=
s are=C2=A0better than those for retail investors. You can subscribe to a p=
roxy-voting service that lets you make all your voting decisions through on=
e online interface, so you are not like literally clipping out proxy cards =
and mailing them back. (Sometimes this gets   hilariously messed up, but no=
t often.)

And so in fact BlackRock seems to devote a fair amount of time and thought =
to voting its shares. And while what I wrote above=C2=A0is=C2=A0most=C2=A0a=
pplicable to BlackRock, you could probably substitute in the names of a doz=
en or so big institutional investors and say many similar things. And=C2=A0=
there are activist hedge funds who make a business of buying concentrated p=
ositions in companies and using their voting power (and proxy fights, etc.)=
 to push for change; obviously=C2=A0they=C2=A0care a lot about voting.
But there are a whole lot of institutional investors, asset managers and mu=
tual funds who are in the business of investing in stocks professionally bu=
t who are not BlackRock. If you are a mutual-fund manager with $1 billion u=
nder management, you might own on the order of  thousands of shares of doze=
ns of companies. Probably you employ multiple professionals to analyze=C2=
=A0companies and decide=C2=A0which stocks to buy. But in terms of=C2=A0voti=
ng=C2=A0your shares, you are perhaps much closer to a retail investor than =
you are to BlackRock:
=09Your thousands of shares in any company are vanishingly unlikely to be d=
ecisive.=09You do not have much soft power to influence issuers=E2=80=99 de=
cisions, so your vote has no symbolic effect.=09There=C2=A0might=C2=A0be so=
me marketing value to your vote =E2=80=94=C2=A0even small investment manage=
rs can raise money by touting their ESG or   anti-ESG voting record =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but if you are just a normal we-try-to-buy-good-stocks manager the=
re=E2=80=99s probably not much.=09You don=E2=80=99t own trillions of dollar=
s of stock, so your bar for economic relevance is high.=09You probably buy =
stocks you like and avoid ones you don=E2=80=99t like: Your =E2=80=9Cvoting=
=E2=80=9D on a company, in a real sense, is buying its stock, not voting yo=
ur shares.=09Yes fine your whole job is paying attention to companies. In=
=C2=A0this you are like BlackRock. You do have some professional fiduciary =
obligation to know what is going on.=09But you have only a few employees, a=
nd their time is better spent on picking stocks to buy or sell than it is o=
n voting.=09Technologically, you too subscribe to a proxy-voting service, s=
o it is administratively easy for you to=C2=A0vote. So you should probably=
=C2=A0vote=C2=A0your shares. You just shouldn=E2=80=99t necessarily=C2=A0th=
ink=C2=A0that hard about it.

That last point is=C2=A0awkward. It is easy for a small institutional inves=
tor to vote all its shares in all the companies it owns: You can just subsc=
ribe to a proxy-voting service, give them a general rule for how you want t=
o vote, and then they will automatically vote your shares for you. You coul=
d have a general blanket rule like =E2=80=9Calways vote to re-elect directo=
rs, ratify auditors and executive pay, and reject any shareholder proposals=
 about writing weird reports.=E2=80=9D (Or =E2=80=9Calways vote for those r=
eports,=E2=80=9D whatever.) And then you could=C2=A0override your general r=
ule if there is some controversy that you particularly care about, or if yo=
u are particularly displeased with some company=E2=80=99s managers, or what=
ever.
Or maybe you would never override that general rule. Maybe it would never b=
e worth it to actually think about how to vote your shares. At a meta-level=
, maybe it=E2=80=99s not worth it to think about when it might be worth it =
to think about how to vote your shares. =E2=80=9CThe odds of us caring are =
so low that we should just throw out all the proxies without reading them t=
o find out if we care,=E2=80=9D might be a rational approach.
  [4]

Rational but embarrassing. Here=E2=80=99s a US Securities and Exchange Comm=
ission  enforcement action from yesterday:

The Securities and Exchange Commission today announced settled charges agai=
nst registered investment adviser, Toews Corporation (=E2=80=9CToews=E2=80=
=9D), for proxy votes on behalf of clients without taking any steps to dete=
rmine whether the votes were in the clients=E2=80=99 best interests, and fo=
r failing to implement policies and procedures reasonably designed to ensur=
e it voted client securities in the best interests of its clients.
The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that from January 2017 through January 2022, =
Toews directed a third-party service provider it engaged to cast proxy vote=
s on behalf of registered investment companies (=E2=80=9CRICs=E2=80=9D) Toe=
ws managed to always vote in favor of proposals put forth by the issuers=E2=
=80=99 management and against any shareholder proposals. =C2=A0According to=
 the SEC=E2=80=99s order, in connection with over two hundred shareholder m=
eetings, Toews caused the third-party service provider to vote the RICs=E2=
=80=99 securities pursuant to this standing instruction without exception a=
nd without any review by Toews of the proxy materials associated with those=
 votes. Toews did not otherwise take steps to determine whether the votes w=
ere cast in the RICs=E2=80=99 best interests and failed to implement polici=
es and procedures reasonably designed to ensure that Toews voted proxies in=
 its clients=E2=80=99 best interests, as required by the Investment Adviser=
s Act of 1940.

For five years, Toews=E2=80=99s proxy voting was on autopilot: It always au=
tomatically voted for=C2=A0whatever management wanted, without reading the =
proxy. It=C2=A0agreed to stop doing that and paid a $150,000 fine. On the o=
ne hand: Sure, yes, it feels unprofessional for a professional money manage=
r to vote its clients=E2=80=99=C2=A0shares automatically without ever givin=
g any thought to any individual vote. On the other hand: It feels=C2=A0unpr=
ofessional, but it is obviously=C2=A0rational?
I guess if you=E2=80=99re the SEC you can=E2=80=99t say that, though. You c=
an=E2=80=99t be like =E2=80=9Cokay fine shareholder voting is mostly a wast=
e of time and nobody should read proxy statements,=E2=80=9D since you=E2=80=
=99re in the business of regulating proxy statements, and since you=E2=80=
=99re regularly=C2=A0adding=C2=A0disclosure and voting requirements to them=
. (The fact that shareholders vote on executive pay is the result of  a 201=
1 SEC rule.) More broadly, the SEC is fundamentally a disclosure regulator,=
 and it is sort of institutionally difficult for the SEC to say that a lot =
of the disclosure it requires isn=E2=80=99t worth reading.
Difficult but not impossible!=C2=A0The two Republican SEC commissioners, He=
ster Peirce and Mark Uyeda,=C2=A0 dissented from the Toews enforcement acti=
on and said, sure, yeah, it=E2=80=99s fine, don=E2=80=99t read the proxy. =
=E2=80=9CImportantly,=E2=80=9D they write,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe Order does not=
 make any findings that the adviser=E2=80=99s clients would have been finan=
cially better off had the adviser cast any of the votes at issue in an alte=
rnative manner=E2=80=9D: Automatic voting feels unprofessional, but it=E2=
=80=99s just vanishingly unlikely that it actually cost=C2=A0Toews=E2=80=99=
s clients any money. And:

The cost of reviewing and analyzing individual matters may outweigh any cor=
responding increase in the value of the issuers=E2=80=99 securities. =E2=80=
=A6
Costs incurred by smaller investment advisers to review and analyze each ma=
tter submitted for a shareholder vote likely will be passed on to clients. =
Toews is not a large adviser with hundreds of employees and trillions under=
 management. According to its most recent Form ADV, Toews reported about $1=
.25 billion in assets under management and 17 employees who perform investm=
ent advisory functions. Given that the majority of investment advisers fall=
 within this category, incorrect implications drawn from the Order potentia=
lly could have wide-ranging consequences.

That's right: The pretty clear implication of this order is that, if you ar=
e a professional money manager, the SEC expects you to=C2=A0read companies=
=E2=80=99 proxy statements before voting your shares at their annual meetin=
gs. And Peirce and Uyeda think that=E2=80=99s probably a waste of time.
  [5]
 They might be right, but it=E2=80=99s a weird thing to say on SEC letterhe=
ad.

