I guess there are three ways to invest in stocks in the modern US:
=09Invest just to make money.=09Invest to promote your values, and you are =
a Democrat.=09Invest to promote your values, and you are a Republican.

I feel very stupid writing that? I don=E2=80=99t know. Broadly speaking, Ap=
proach 1 has been the dominant approach in most of the history of investing=
. Approach 2 =E2=80=94=C2=A0using your investment dollars to promote leftis=
h=C2=A0social goals, to try to push public companies to take action on clim=
ate change, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0is sometimes called =E2=80=9Csocially respo=
nsible investing,=E2=80=9D but these days it tends to be loosely lumped int=
o the category of =E2=80=9CESG,=E2=80=9D environmental, social and governan=
ce investing. (Meanwhile=C2=A0  purist ESG investors say, no, we are just i=
nvesting to make money, but we are considering ESG risk factors that might =
cause us to lose money. Never mind!)
Meanwhile if you are a Republican you won=E2=80=99t like the=C2=A0ESG/socia=
lly responsible approach: You might not want to reduce fossil-fuel use to=
=C2=A0address climate change, and you might think that the social goals of =
ESG-ish funds are bad. And so there is a natural Republican backlash that s=
ays: No, don=E2=80=99t do ESG, do Approach 1; invest only to make money.=C2=
=A0 Republican politicians try to ban ESG, and   Republican fund managers r=
un=C2=A0funds that write strongly worded letters to companies telling them =
not to care about society or the environment and focus on making money. I s=
ometimes call this =E2=80=9Canti-ESG.=E2=80=9D It is ostensibly Approach 1 =
(invest to make money, not to promote values), though often it seems like s=
ome value judgments creep into it. It=E2=80=99s just that those value judgm=
ents are opposed to the judgments of standard ESG managers.
But, conceptually, the full-on Approach 3 is still available: Be an explici=
tly=C2=A0socially responsible/ESG fund, but take a different (right-wing) v=
iew of what counts as socially responsible.   Here=E2=80=99s a guy:

Enter Inspire Investing. [Robert] Netzly=E2=80=99s seven-year-old firm over=
sees exchange-traded funds with tickers such as BIBL, BLES, GLRY and WWJD, =
short for =E2=80=9CWhat Would Jesus Do?=E2=80=9D This year, his biggest ETF=
, Inspire 100 (ticker BIBL), is posting wider losses than the S&P 500. =E2=
=80=A6
Which companies qualify for =E2=80=9CGod=E2=80=99s portfolios=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0at Inspire? The lines can get blurry. Inspire screens companies by a var=
iety of categories under the =E2=80=9CE,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CS=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
and =E2=80=9CG=E2=80=9D=C2=A0of ESG. But it=E2=80=99s the S=E2=80=94social=
=E2=80=94where things get particularly contentious for Netzly. =E2=80=A6
Inspire views supporting LGBTQ rights, covering travel for reproductive hea=
lth, stem cell research and in vitro fertilization as big negatives. So, to=
o, selling alcohol, cannabis, tobacco, gambling and distributing pornograph=
y. It endorses companies it deems worthy, engages with those it hopes to co=
nvert and excludes or divests from ones that it finds =E2=80=9Cimmoral.=E2=
=80=9D
The result: a list of companies that=E2=80=94while not necessarily declared=
 =E2=80=9Cblessed=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94generally square with Netzly=E2=80=99s b=
eliefs.

There is the awkward question of labeling. You don=E2=80=99t want to call t=
his =E2=80=9CESG,=E2=80=9D because that term has become identified with App=
roach 2, and he=E2=80=99s marketing to Republicans.=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=E2=80=98=
The Pollyanna in me wishes that there could be a two-party ESG system,=E2=
=80=99=C2=A0Netzly said,=E2=80=9D which makes sense as a matter of tidy sym=
metrical categorization but doesn=E2=80=99t work for marketing:

A few months ago, phones began lighting up at Inspire. Elon Musk, the world=
=E2=80=99s richest person, was attacking ESG as =E2=80=9Cthe devil incarnat=
e.=E2=80=9D DeSantis, the Florida governor and White House hopeful, was pil=
ing on. Fox News firebrand Tucker Carlson, along with right-wing radio host=
 Glenn Beck, were blaming ESG for everything from high gasoline prices to e=
conomic trouble in Sri Lanka.
If ESG was so bad, Inspire clients wanted to know why was Netzly wrapping h=
imself in label? His answer: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m not anymore.=E2=80=9D He =
formally renounced the tag and rallied behind the so-called anti-woke campa=
ign.
=E2=80=9CEvery conservative pundit is calling ESG evil. We just can't count=
eract that narrative,=E2=80=9D Netzly said. =E2=80=9CIt's exponentially inc=
reasing.=E2=80=9D
In a blog post, he struck a different tone. =E2=80=9CThe burning intoleranc=
e of the left has hit a gas line in the ESG party hall, escalating the flam=
es to such heights that it has become necessary for us to abandon the build=
ing,=E2=80=9D Netzly said on Aug. 18.

Sure okay. Elsewhere in, uh, anti-ESG metaphors, here=E2=80=99s a Bloomberg=
 article titled =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98Dilbert=E2=80=99 Becomes the Voice of ESG=
 Opposition=E2=80=9D:
Even the creator of the =E2=80=9CDilbert=E2=80=9D cartoon is taking potshot=
s at an investment strategy that focuses on risks tied to the environment, =
social and corporate governance. In a series of illustrations published las=
t week, author Scott Adams criticized ESG, comparing it to a =E2=80=9Ccolic=
ky=E2=80=9D baby with =E2=80=9Cfirehouse diarrhea.=E2=80=9D
Great.

