<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Shareholder voting</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked a few times recently about a st=
ylized fact of US public companies, which is that retail shareholders don=
=E2=80=99t vote. When a company has its annual meeting and sends out proxy =
statements and asks its shareholders to vote on questions like =E2=80=9Csho=
uld our board of directors be re-elected=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdo you appro=
ve of management=E2=80=99s compensation plan=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdo you a=
pprove of=C2=A0our audit firm=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cshould we write a repor=
t about our greenhouse gas emissions,=E2=80=9D its ordinary individual shar=
eholders throw those proxy statements in the garbage and do not vote on tho=
se questions.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One reason that retail shareholders don=E2=80=
=99t vote is that it is hard to reach them: They have busy lives, they get =
a lot of junk mail, they throw it all away. Plus the company itself general=
ly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285535=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMTAvcH=
JpdmF0ZS1mdW5kcy1hcmUtdGhlLW5ldy1wdWJsaWMtZnVuZHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkyMTIyX01PT=
kVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09=
MjIwOTIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd902926d"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">  won=E2=80=99t know who its retail shareholders are</a>, and will=
 have to communicate using a multi-tiered indirect approach (sending proxie=
s to brokers who send them to shareholders, etc.) that doesn=E2=80=99t reac=
h shareholders very efficiently.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another reason that retail shareholders don=E2=
=80=99t vote is that it would be an insane use of their time. If you own sh=
ares in 50 companies, and you want to vote those shares in an informed way,=
 you have to read 50 proxy statements each year. Each proxy might be 50 to =
100 pages long, so you are talking about thousands of pages of reading. Her=
e is Exxon Mobil Corp.=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdh=
ci9kYXRhLzM0MDg4LzAwMDExOTMxMjUyMjA5ODMxNC9kMjgwMjU5ZGRlZjE0YS5odG0jdG9jMjg=
wMjU5XzEw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc75002ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> proxy statement</a> f=
or its 2022 annual meeting, which runs to 86 pages. Shareholders have to vo=
te to re-elect 11 members of the board of directors. They have to vote to r=
atify Exxon=E2=80=99s independent auditors and to approve its executive com=
pensation. And then there are seven proposals that shareholders have made =
=E2=80=94 some of the summaries on the proxy card are=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cremove =
executive perquisites,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Creport on scenario analysis,=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9Creport on plastic production=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0that also=
 require votes. So just for Exxon you need to come to a view=C2=A0on 20 dif=
ferent proposals. You have 49 more proxies to read.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of these votes are binding. If a majority=
 of=C2=A0shareholders vote against a public company=E2=80=99s director=C2=
=A0in an ordinary uncontested vote, that director=C2=A0will probably have t=
o submit a resignation, but the board generally has the option to reject th=
e resignation: The shareholder vote itself is not enough to remove that dir=
ector. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2912493=
2.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMj=
EvY3J5cHRvLXRyYWNlci1jaGFpbmFseXNpcy1idXN0cy1iaXRjb2luLWJ0Yy1hbm9ueW1pdHk_Y=
21waWQ9QkJEMDkyMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5l=
d3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB9f1013e9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">  auditor ratification</a>=C2=A0and <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuaHVnaGVzaHViYmFyZC5jb20vbmV3cy9zZWMtaXNzdWVzLWZpbmFsLXNheS1vbi1wYXk=
tcnVsZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB28a3a0f1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> executive compensation=
</a> votes are nonbinding; it is embarrassing for the company to lose them =
but has no obvious immediate effect. The shareholder proposals are especial=
ly nonbinding: They generally call for the company to write reports about t=
hings that the shareholders don=E2=80=99t like=C2=A0(plastic production, et=
c.). Even if a majority of shareholders vote for these proposals,=C2=A0the =
company is not required to write the reports. Even if it does write the rep=
orts, it doesn=E2=80=99t have to do anything about them. There is not reall=
y a mechanism for the shareholders to say =E2=80=9Cstop producing plastics=
=E2=80=9D and make the company actually do it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if you are a shareholder and you hold 100 s=
hares of stock of Exxon, you might reasonably think: =E2=80=9CNone of this =
makes any difference to me at all. I just want my stock to go up, and none =
of this stuff will make my stock go up or down no matter how I vote. I have=
 better things to do.=E2=80=9D So you throw out the proxy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, to be fair, sometimes there are important=
 binding votes. If a public company agrees to be acquired in a merger, its =
shareholders will have to vote to approve the merger; if it doesn=E2=80=99t=
 get enough votes then the merger won=E2=80=99t happen. If the company is t=
rading at $10 and the merger price is $15, and you don=E2=80=99t vote and t=
he merger fails, you will miss out on $5 per share. Sometimes companies nee=
d shareholder approval to, say, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjQvYW1jLXMtYXBlcy1taWdodC1zdGljay1hcm91bmQ_Y21waWQ9=
QkJEMDkyMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR=
0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB97464e6b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  issue more stock</a>, or <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDEvdGhlLXRydW1wLXNwYWMtbmVlZHM=
tbW9yZS10aW1lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MjEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdX=
RtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDkyMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzd=
HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2f2fa201" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  extend their deadline =
to do a deal</a>, and getting or not getting that approval will make a real=
 economic difference. Sometimes an activist will launch a proxy fight, whic=
h will lead to a=C2=A0<em>binding=C2=A0</em>shareholder vote on two differe=
nt slates of possible board members with different strategies.=C2=A0In fact=
 this <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285=
535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS9zZWFyY2g_cT1FeHhvbitMb3N0K2ErQ2xpbWF0ZSt=
Qcm94eStGaWdodCZybHo9MUM1Q0hGQV9lblVTODA3VVM4MDcmb3E9RXh4b24rTG9zdCthK0NsaW=
1hdGUrUHJveHkrRmlnaHQmYXFzPWNocm9tZS4uNjlpNTdqNjlpNjBsMy4yNzBqMGo0JnNvdXJjZ=
WlkPWNocm9tZSZpZT1VVEYtOA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfed03121" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> happe=
ned at Exxon in 2021</a>: An activist ran a proxy fight to put new director=
s on the board to try to move the company toward renewables faster; the act=
ivist won.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you get a proxy statement like that, you mi=
ght want to vote your shares, because your vote could have an impact on the=
 value of your stock. But your vote won=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0<=
/em>much of an impact, because you hold 100 shares and there are billions o=
f shares. In Exxon=E2=80=99s proxy fight last year, there were 16 candidate=
s, and the=C2=A012 candidates who got the most votes were elected to the bo=
ard. The person in 12th place (the lowest-ranked winner)=C2=A0<a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMzQwODgvMDAwMDAzNDA4ODIxMD=
AwMDMxL3hvbS0yMDIxMDUyNi5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1e565b8a" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
got 1,174,445,208 votes</a>; the person in 13th place (the top loser) got 1=
,173,545,328. That=E2=80=99s a difference of 899,880 shares out of almost 1=
.2 billion, or about 0.08%, an incredibly close and hard-fought proxy fight=
. Also though that margin is=C2=A0like 9,000 times your little block of 100=
 shares. Your vote wouldn=E2=80=99t have mattered. And that=E2=80=99s about=
 as close as proxy fights realistically get. Even in this hard-fought bindi=
ng contest about the strategic direction of Exxon, it=C2=A0was still a wast=
e of time for <em>you=C2=A0</em>to vote.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, even if you thought =E2=80=9Cwell I=E2=
=80=99ll vote on things like mergers and proxy fights where it might matter=
, but not on uncontested director elections where it doesn=E2=80=99t,=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0you=E2=80=99d have a problem, which is that you=E2=80=99d have to=
=C2=A0<em>pay attention and find out</em>. What, you=E2=80=99re going to re=
ad every 80-page proxy statement to see if there=E2=80=99s anything good in=
 it? A much easier heuristic is: =E2=80=9CMost votes don=E2=80=99t matter, =
and even on the ones that do matter my vote is unlikely to be decisive, so =
I am going to throw out all the proxy statements without reading them.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is just obvious normal stuff. If you are =
an individual shareholder, what you do is (1) buy stock in companies that y=
ou like, (2) not buy stock in companies that you don=E2=80=99t like, and (3=
) if you start to dislike a company whose stock you own, you sell it. A fou=
rth approach of buying stock in companies and trying to=C2=A0<em>change the=
m=C2=A0</em>via shareholder voting would be=C2=A0extremely odd, which is wh=
y very few retail investors do it.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are the gigantic institutional asset ma=
nager BlackRock Inc., your calculation is very different, in a number of wa=
ys:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You own millions of shares of every p=
ublic company, so your vote, on contested binding issues, matters. You migh=
t very well be the deciding vote on a merger or a proxy fight, which might =
make a material difference to the value of your shares.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Even on the nonbinding stuff, you will care, because =
you own every public company and you are playing a long game. You might dec=
ide something like =E2=80=9Cour companies should be reducing greenhouse gas=
 emissions,=E2=80=9D and then you might think about how to make them do tha=
t. There are approaches that are <em>nonbinding=C2=A0</em>but <em>persuasiv=
e.=C2=A0</em>(You might have quiet one-on-one chats with the company=E2=80=
=99s managers about emissions.) But as a huge shareholder there are also ap=
proaches that are binding. (You might support a proxy fight, as BlackRock a=
pparently did at Exxon, to throw out directors who don=E2=80=99t do what yo=
u want.) And then everything else sort of exists in the shadow of those bin=
ding approaches. If you are BlackRock and you think a company pollutes too =
much, you might vote your shares in support of a nonbinding shareholder res=
olution saying =E2=80=9Cthe company should write a report about pollution.=
=E2=80=9D If that resolution gets majority support =E2=80=94=C2=A0or even a=
 large minority =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=C2=A0will be embarrassing for the direc=
tors. If they continue to pollute too much, you might vote no on executive =
pay or director re-election: again nonbinding, but even more embarrassing, =
and also a=C2=A0signal that next year you might support an activist proxy f=
ight and actually throw out the directors.=C2=A0All of this stuff is subtle=
 and coded, but the point is that the shareholder vote is one tool that Bla=
ckRock has to express its desires, and BlackRock=E2=80=99s desires matter a=
 lot to public-company executives because BlackRock owns like 8% of their s=
tock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Voting on the nonbinding stu=
ff might have some marketing value. =E2=80=9CWe care about the environment =
and pressure companies to do better, as you can see from our voting record,=
=E2=80=9D you might want to be able to say, in marketing your funds to pote=
ntial investors.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> Environmental, social and governance investing is hot (though controve=
rsial) now, and voting on shareholder proposals is a way to signal your ESG=
 commitments.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Because you own tril=
lions of dollars of stock, your bar for economic relevance is in some sense=
 lower. If you think that writing a report on greenhouse gas emissions migh=
t add 0.01% to the value of Exxon=E2=80=99s stock, well, BlackRock owns lik=
e $24 billion of Exxon stock, so adding 0.01% would be worth $2.4 million t=
o BlackRock=E2=80=99s investors. Worth an afternoon of someone=E2=80=99s ti=
me reading a proxy. But if you=E2=80=99re an individual with 100 shares, th=
at 0.01% is worth about $0.92 to you.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">Unlike retail shareholders, you=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>just s=
ell shares in the companies you don=E2=80=99t like: A lot of your money is =
in index funds, which are mandated to hold all the companies. So it is rati=
onal to try to pressure them with voting rather than just dumping their sto=
cks when they do things you don=E2=80=99t like.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Your whole job is paying attention to the important issues at=
 the companies you invest in, unlike a retail investor who has a day job an=
d has to read proxy statements in the evening after a long day at work. You=
 are a fiduciary for your clients, so you have to do a good and careful job=
 of paying attention.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have tho=
usands of employees, so you can have a couple of them specialize in reading=
 proxies. They=E2=80=99ll get good at it, they=E2=80=99ll know what to look=
 for, so they can use their time efficiently rather than reading every 80-p=
age proxy cover to cover with a pen in their hands. And because you care mo=
stly about systemic issues, they can develop pretty good rules of thumb abo=
ut what sorts of proposals they should and should not vote for.<a class=3D"=
footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impo=
rtant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Just technologically, the voting=
=C2=A0systems for institutional investors are=C2=A0better than those for re=
tail investors. You can subscribe to a proxy-voting service that lets you m=
ake all your voting decisions through one online interface, so you are not =
like literally clipping out proxy cards and mailing them back. (Sometimes t=
his gets <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.=
285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMDUt=
MTMvdC1yb3dlLXByaWNlLXZvdGVkLWZvci10aGUtZGVsbC1idXlvdXQtYnktYWNjaWRlbnQ_Y21=
waWQ9QkJEMDkyMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3=
NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB20416804" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">  hilariously messed up</a>, but not often.)=
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so in fact BlackRock seems to devote a fai=
r amount of time and thought to voting its shares. And while what I wrote a=
bove=C2=A0is=C2=A0<em>most=C2=A0</em>applicable to BlackRock, you could pro=
bably substitute in the names of a dozen or so big institutional investors =
and say many similar things. And=C2=A0there are activist hedge funds who ma=
ke a business of buying concentrated positions in companies and using their=
 voting power (and proxy fights, etc.) to push for change; obviously=C2=A0<=
em>they=C2=A0</em>care a lot about voting.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are a whole lot of institutional inv=
estors, asset managers and mutual funds who are in the business of investin=
g in stocks professionally but who are not BlackRock. If you are a mutual-f=
und manager with $1 billion under management, you might own on the order of=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285535/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzkzMjAwMC8wMDAwOTMyMDAw=
MjIwMDAwMDQveHNsRm9ybTEzRl9YMDEvMTNGXzJRLjIwMjIueG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB39cec03b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> thousands of shares of dozens of companies</a>. Proba=
bly you employ multiple professionals to analyze=C2=A0companies and decide=
=C2=A0which stocks to buy. But in terms of=C2=A0<em>voting=C2=A0</em>your s=
hares, you are perhaps much closer to a retail investor than you are to Bla=
ckRock:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your thousands of shares in any compa=
ny are vanishingly unlikely to be decisive.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">You do not have much soft power to influence issuers=E2=80=99 dec=
isions, so your vote has no symbolic effect.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">There=C2=A0<em>might=C2=A0</em>be some marketing value to your v=
ote =E2=80=94=C2=A0even small investment managers can raise money by toutin=
g their ESG or <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/291=
24932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMj=
ItMDktMDEvdGhlLXRydW1wLXNwYWMtbmVlZHMtbW9yZS10aW1lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MjEyMl9NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTIyMDkyMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC2f2fa20=
1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  anti-ESG</a> voting record =E2=80=94=C2=A0but if you are jus=
t a normal we-try-to-buy-good-stocks manager there=E2=80=99s probably not m=
uch.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t own trillio=
ns of dollars of stock, so your bar for economic relevance is high.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You probably buy stocks you like and avoi=
d ones you don=E2=80=99t like: Your =E2=80=9Cvoting=E2=80=9D on a company, =
in a real sense, is buying its stock, not voting your shares.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Yes fine your whole job is paying attention to =
companies. In=C2=A0this you are like BlackRock. You do have some profession=
al fiduciary obligation to know what is going on.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">But you have only a few employees, and their time is better=
 spent on picking stocks to buy or sell than it is on voting.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Technologically, you too subscribe to a proxy-v=
oting service, so it is administratively easy for you to=C2=A0<em>vote</em>=
. So you should probably=C2=A0<em>vote=C2=A0</em>your shares. You just shou=
ldn=E2=80=99t necessarily=C2=A0<em>think=C2=A0</em>that hard about it.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That last point is=C2=A0awkward. It is easy fo=
r a small institutional investor to vote all its shares in all the companie=
s it owns: You can just subscribe to a proxy-voting service, give them a ge=
neral rule for how you want to vote, and then they will automatically vote =
your shares for you. You could have a general blanket rule like =E2=80=9Cal=
ways vote to re-elect directors, ratify auditors and executive pay, and rej=
ect any shareholder proposals about writing weird reports.=E2=80=9D (Or =E2=
=80=9Calways vote for those reports,=E2=80=9D whatever.) And then you could=
=C2=A0override your general rule if there is some controversy that you part=
icularly care about, or if you are particularly displeased with some compan=
y=E2=80=99s managers, or whatever.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or maybe you would never override that general=
 rule. Maybe it would never be worth it to actually think about how to vote=
 your shares. At a meta-level, maybe it=E2=80=99s not worth it to think abo=
ut when it might be worth it to think about how to vote your shares. =E2=80=
=9CThe odds of us caring are so low that we should just throw out all the p=
roxies without reading them to find out if we care,=E2=80=9D might be a rat=
ional approach.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rational but embarrassing. Here=E2=80=99s a US=
 Securities and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9lbmZvcmNlL2lhL=
TYxMzktcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd3971224" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> enforcement action</a=
> from yesterday:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today a=
nnounced settled charges against registered investment adviser, Toews Corpo=
ration (=E2=80=9CToews=E2=80=9D), for proxy votes on behalf of clients with=
out taking any steps to determine whether the votes were in the clients=E2=
=80=99 best interests, and for failing to implement policies and procedures=
 reasonably designed to ensure it voted client securities in the best inter=
ests of its clients.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s order finds that from Januar=
y 2017 through January 2022, Toews directed a third-party service provider =
it engaged to cast proxy votes on behalf of registered investment companies=
 (=E2=80=9CRICs=E2=80=9D) Toews managed to always vote in favor of proposal=
s put forth by the issuers=E2=80=99 management and against any shareholder =
proposals. =C2=A0According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, in connection with o=
ver two hundred shareholder meetings, Toews caused the third-party service =
provider to vote the RICs=E2=80=99 securities pursuant to this standing ins=
truction without exception and without any review by Toews of the proxy mat=
erials associated with those votes. Toews did not otherwise take steps to d=
etermine whether the votes were cast in the RICs=E2=80=99 best interests an=
d failed to implement policies and procedures reasonably designed to ensure=
 that Toews voted proxies in its clients=E2=80=99 best interests, as requir=
ed by the Investment Advisers Act of 1940.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For five years, Toews=E2=80=99s proxy voting w=
as on autopilot: It always automatically voted for=C2=A0whatever management=
 wanted, without reading the proxy. It=C2=A0agreed to stop doing that and p=
aid a $150,000 fine. On the one hand: Sure, yes, it feels unprofessional fo=
r a professional money manager to vote its clients=E2=80=99=C2=A0shares aut=
omatically without ever giving any thought to any individual vote. On the o=
ther hand: It <em>feels=C2=A0</em>unprofessional, but it is obviously=C2=A0=
rational?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess if you=E2=80=99re the SEC you can=E2=
=80=99t say that, though. You can=E2=80=99t be like =E2=80=9Cokay fine shar=
eholder voting is mostly a waste of time and nobody should read proxy state=
ments,=E2=80=9D since you=E2=80=99re in the business of regulating proxy st=
atements, and since you=E2=80=99re regularly=C2=A0<em>adding=C2=A0</em>disc=
losure and voting requirements to them. (The fact that shareholders vote on=
 executive pay is the result of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLzIwM=
TEvMjAxMS0yNS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf1041b77" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a 2011 SEC r=
ule</a>.) More broadly, the SEC is fundamentally a disclosure regulator, an=
d it is sort of institutionally difficult for the SEC to say that a lot of =
the disclosure it requires isn=E2=80=99t worth reading.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Difficult but not impossible!=C2=A0The two Rep=
ublican SEC commissioners, Hester Peirce and Mark Uyeda,=C2=A0<a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3N0YXRlbWVudC9wZWlyY2UtdXllZGEtc3RhdGVtZW50LXRvZXdzLWNvcn=
BvcmF0aW9u/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBee64177c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> dissented from the T=
oews enforcement action</a> and said, sure, yeah, it=E2=80=99s fine, don=E2=
=80=99t read the proxy. =E2=80=9CImportantly,=E2=80=9D they write,=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cthe Order does not make any findings that the adviser=E2=80=99s clien=
ts would have been financially better off had the adviser cast any of the v=
otes at issue in an alternative manner=E2=80=9D: Automatic voting <em>feels=
</em> unprofessional, but it=E2=80=99s just vanishingly unlikely that it ac=
tually cost=C2=A0Toews=E2=80=99s clients any money. And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The cost of reviewing and analyzing individual=
 matters may outweigh any corresponding increase in the value of the issuer=
s=E2=80=99 securities. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Costs incurred by smaller investment advisers =
to review and analyze each matter submitted for a shareholder vote likely w=
ill be passed on to clients. Toews is not a large adviser with hundreds of =
employees and trillions under management. According to its most recent Form=
 ADV, Toews reported about $1.25 billion in assets under management and 17 =
employees who perform investment advisory functions. Given that the majorit=
y of investment advisers fall within this category, incorrect implications =
drawn from the Order potentially could have wide-ranging consequences.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That's right: The pretty clear implication of =
this order is that, if you are a professional money manager, the SEC expect=
s you to=C2=A0read companies=E2=80=99 proxy statements before voting your s=
hares at their annual meetings. And Peirce and Uyeda think that=E2=80=99s p=
robably a waste of time.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> They might be right, but it=E2=80=99s a weird thing to say on SEC lett=
erhead.</p>
