<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess there are three ways to invest in stoc=
ks in the modern US:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Invest just to make money.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Invest to promote your values, and you are a=
 Democrat.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Invest to promote your =
values, and you are a Republican.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel very stupid writing that? I don=E2=80=
=99t know. Broadly speaking, Approach 1 has been the dominant approach in m=
ost of the history of investing. Approach 2 =E2=80=94=C2=A0using your inves=
tment dollars to promote leftish=C2=A0social goals, to try to push public c=
ompanies to take action on climate change, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0is sometimes=
 called =E2=80=9Csocially responsible investing,=E2=80=9D but these days it=
 tends to be loosely lumped into the category of =E2=80=9CESG,=E2=80=9D env=
ironmental, social and governance investing. (Meanwhile=C2=A0<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjIvbWVtZS1zdG9jay12YWN=
hdGlvbi1pcy1vdmVyP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MjEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haW=
wmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDkyMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZ=
XlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB17056067" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  purist ESG investors=
 say</a>, no, we are just investing to make money, but we are considering E=
SG risk factors that might cause us to lose money. Never mind!)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile if you are a Republican you won=E2=
=80=99t like the=C2=A0ESG/socially responsible approach: You might not want=
 to reduce fossil-fuel use to=C2=A0address climate change, and you might th=
ink that the social goals of ESG-ish funds are bad. And so there is a natur=
al Republican backlash that says: No, don=E2=80=99t do ESG, do Approach 1; =
invest only to make money.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjQvYW1jLXMtYXBlcy1taWdodC1zdGljay1hcm91bmQ_Y21waWQ9=
QkJEMDkyMTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR=
0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cC97464e6b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> Republican politicians</a> try to ban ESG, and <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDcvZG9lcy=
1lbG9uLW11c2sta25vdy1ob3ctbWVyZ2Vycy13b3JrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MjEyMl9NT05FWVNUV=
UZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDky=
MSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc29aca76" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">  Republican fund managers</a> run=C2=A0funds that write strongly worded=
 letters to companies telling them <em>not</em> to care about society or th=
e environment and focus on making money. I sometimes call this =E2=80=9Cant=
i-ESG.=E2=80=9D It is ostensibly Approach 1 (invest to make money, not to p=
romote values), though often it seems like some value judgments creep into =
it. It=E2=80=99s just that those value judgments are opposed to the judgmen=
ts of standard ESG managers.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, conceptually, the full-on Approach 3 is s=
till available: Be an explicitly=C2=A0socially responsible/ESG fund, but ta=
ke a different (right-wing) view of what counts as socially responsible. <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29124932.285535/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMjEvZXZhbmdlbGl=
jYWwtaW52ZXN0b3Itcy0yLWJpbGxpb24tZnVuZC1mb3ItZmFpdGgtYmFzZWQtc3RvY2tzP2NtcG=
lkPUJCRDA5MjEyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzb=
GV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDkyMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB99faaea3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  Here=E2=80=99s a guy</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Enter Inspire Investing. [Robert] Netzly=E2=80=
=99s seven-year-old firm oversees exchange-traded funds with tickers such a=
s BIBL, BLES, GLRY and WWJD, short for =E2=80=9CWhat Would Jesus Do?=E2=80=
=9D This year, his biggest ETF, Inspire 100 (ticker BIBL), is posting wider=
 losses than the S&amp;P 500. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Which companies qualify for =E2=80=9CGod=E2=80=
=99s portfolios=E2=80=9D=C2=A0at Inspire? The lines can get blurry. Inspire=
 screens companies by a variety of categories under the =E2=80=9CE,=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9CS=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and =E2=80=9CG=E2=80=9D=C2=A0of ESG. But it=E2=
=80=99s the S=E2=80=94social=E2=80=94where things get particularly contenti=
ous for Netzly. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Inspire views supporting LGBTQ rights, coverin=
g travel for reproductive health, stem cell research and in vitro fertiliza=
tion as big negatives. So, too, selling alcohol, cannabis, tobacco, gamblin=
g and distributing pornography. It endorses companies it deems worthy, enga=
ges with those it hopes to convert and excludes or divests from ones that i=
t finds =E2=80=9Cimmoral.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The result: a list of companies that=E2=80=94w=
hile not necessarily declared =E2=80=9Cblessed=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94generally s=
quare with Netzly=E2=80=99s beliefs.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is the awkward question of labeling. You=
 don=E2=80=99t want to call this =E2=80=9CESG,=E2=80=9D because that term h=
as become identified with Approach 2, and he=E2=80=99s marketing to Republi=
cans.=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=E2=80=98The Pollyanna in me wishes that there could be=
 a two-party ESG system,=E2=80=99=C2=A0Netzly said,=E2=80=9D which makes se=
nse as a matter of tidy symmetrical categorization but doesn=E2=80=99t work=
 for marketing:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few months ago, phones began lighting up at =
Inspire. Elon Musk, the world=E2=80=99s richest person, was attacking ESG a=
s =E2=80=9Cthe devil incarnate.=E2=80=9D DeSantis, the Florida governor and=
 White House hopeful, was piling on. Fox News firebrand Tucker Carlson, alo=
ng with right-wing radio host Glenn Beck, were blaming ESG for everything f=
rom high gasoline prices to economic trouble in Sri Lanka.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If ESG was so bad, Inspire clients wanted to k=
now why was Netzly wrapping himself in label? His answer: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99m not anymore.=E2=80=9D He formally renounced the tag and rallied behind=
 the so-called anti-woke campaign.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CEvery conservative pundit is calling =
ESG evil. We just can't counteract that narrative,=E2=80=9D Netzly said. =
=E2=80=9CIt's exponentially increasing.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a blog post, he struck a different tone. =
=E2=80=9CThe burning intolerance of the left has hit a gas line in the ESG =
party hall, escalating the flames to such heights that it has become necess=
ary for us to abandon the building,=E2=80=9D Netzly said on Aug. 18.</p>
</blockquote>
